snippet.textDisplay:
Where I live shimano oil is very very expensive and hard to find. So I use for my brakes ferodo fbm100 (lhm+) which is a mineral oil intended to be used on hydraulic suspension and brake systems and has a boiling point of 250c-380c (shimano has a boiling point of 280c) and a viscocity of 18cst@40c (I think slightly heavier than shimano).

Drug store mineral oil will not make any harm but is quite heavy and will make brakes fill sluggish, especially in very low temperatures.

snippet.textDisplay: I have the similar brakes on my 10kw electric bike (Simano M395 but the colour is white) and I have been using rapeseed oil in them going on 5 years now. Never had an issue, and the stopping power is just as good. I'm sure that almost everybody will have some sort of cooking oil in their kitchen somewhere. I did this at first as an emergency as I never had any of the proper mineral oil, but after using it for a while with no noticeable decrease in stopping power, I just kept on using it. I would say that this method may even be the cheapest way to obtain brake oil.😁

In trial bikes with hydraulic v-brake, it's common to replace the mineral oil with water (preferably distilled) or a 50/50 mix of water and antifreeze (from any car shop) so parts will last longer and behave more consistently.
When making that change, it's very noticable the lever becomes easier to press and returns quicker.
Nothing like this was noticeable with the baby oil?

snippet.textDisplay: As a bicycle mechanic for roundabout 10years I tested the same thing with various liquids. Baby Oil was one of my favorites. I started this after a colleague of mine was telling the story of him riding through Africa with a HS33 and no proper oil within a 300mile radius. So he just used water. Aslong as the temps are fine you can use almost any liquid that doesnt dissolve your seals.

snippet.textDisplay:
After seeing seth post about doing this a year ago i decided to do the same experiment on my bike (Trek remedy 9 with shimano XT brakes front and rear). Well 9 months and about 1500 miles later (i ride a lot) the seals in the lever gave way leading to the dredded leaver stick problem where the piston goes in and stays in. I have since replaced the brakes with new ones (some more XT's, Lever, hose and caliper) and filled with proper mineral oil. So, in conclusion, on a bike that got a lot of use in XC and Enduro riding (with a good bit of downhill too) the baby oil seems to work for a bit till it destroys your seals and kills the breaks for good. Cannot recommend.


EDIT: and yeah on uplift days the oil would get pretty hot and stink of baby oil fragrance really strongly
